violations.description:
"An active <area> element has no alt text. This is an accessibility failure.
Image maps are single images with several clickable areas. Each of these visually defined areas must have an alternate text, and the entire image must have its own alt text as well.
Example: An image map of the United States with each state set as an area. Each state should have its name, size, and coordinates included in its alt text, and the entire image map should have meaningful alt text, e.g., ""Map of the United States with clickable state areas."""
violations.errorMessage: Missing: alt text on active image map area
violations.recommendation:
Action: Add alternative text to each <area> element.
 
How to fix:
Use ONE of the following methods:
 
Good:
• title attribute
 
Better:
• aria-label
 
Best:
• aria-labelledby attribute
• alt attribute
 
To accommodate for different browsers and devices:
• Use every image map only once. If the same image map is used in another place, or multiple images use the same image map, the map must be duplicated and given different IDs.
• Place the <map> element as a direct sibling to the image.
• For mobile: Provide redundant text links on the same page, to replace possibly non-functional image maps.

How to fix:
Follow these steps:
 
1. Identify the ARIA role that best represents the element's function.

5. Make sure the value of each ARIA state attribute updates as needed to reflect the element's current state.

violations.description: An element with the aria-hidden="true" attribute contains focusable elements.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Make sure elements with aria-hidden="true" do not contain focusable elements.
 
How to fix:
Use one or more of the following methods:
 
1. Use aria-hidden="true" ONLY on elements whose content is decorative-only, repetitive, or otherwise not informative for screen reader and assistive tech users.
 
2. Restructure the code so that the focusable elements are not children of the hidden element:
  2a. Where appropriate, make the child elements non-focusable (by applying the disabled attribute) or non-tabbable (by applying tabindex="-1").
  2b. Where appropriate, hide elements from all users by applying hidden, display:none, or visibility:hidden attributes.

violations.recommendation:
Action: Be sure to include all appropriate child elements and roles within the ARIA parent roles that require them.

How to fix:
1. Identify the ARIA role that best identifies the element's function.
2. In the browser accessibility pane, examine the element serving as the managing control to verify it has the correct "parent" role attribute.
3. Identify the elements serving as managed controls and add the appropriate "child" roles to them.
4. Apply any ARIA state and property attributes that are required for the given roles.
5. Make sure the value of each ARIA property attribute is correct.
6. Make sure the value of each ARIA state attribute updates as needed to reflect the element's current state.

violations.description: Certain ARIA roles must be contained by specific parent roles, or they will be unable to perform their intended accessibility functions.
violations.errorMessage: ARIA child role missing parent role
violations.recommendation:
Action: Be sure to contain all child roles within their appropriate ARIA parent roles, as required.
 
How to fix:
1. Identify the ARIA role that best represents the element's function.
2. In the browser accessibility pane, examine the elements serving as the managed controls to verify they have the correct "child" role attributes.
3. Add parent role:
 3a. Identify (or add) the element serving as the managing control, and
 3b. Add the appropriate "parent" role to it.
4. Apply any ARIA state and property attributes that are required for the given roles:
  4a. Make sure the value of each ARIA property attribute is correct.
  4b. Make sure the value of each ARIA state attribute updates as needed to reflect the element's current state.

violations.description: The aria-roledescription attribute is used incorrectly. It may be used ONLY on elements with a supported role, i.e., an implicit or explicit role value.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Use aria-roledescription only on elements that have an explicit or implicit ARIA role.
 
How to fix:
1. Examine all elements that use the aria-roledescription attribute.
2. Do the elements have an implicit or explicit role value or values?
3. If not, remove the attribute.
 
Implicit role (definition): An implicit ARIA role is derived from the element itself. For example, a <button> element has an implicit role of button.
 
For a list of HTML elements and their implicit roles, see ARIA in HTML. Elements noted as having "No corresponding role" have no implicit ARIA role.
 
Explicit role (definition): You can add an explicit ARIA role using the role attribute.
 
Example: Adding role="button" to a <div> element changes the element's role to button.

violations.description:
An invalid ARIA role value is in use; it will not correctly convey the element's purpose.
Valid roles have correct spelling, match existing ARIA role values, and are not abstract roles.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Add a valid value to the role attribute. Use ONLY valid values for all ARIA roles.
 
How to fix:
1. Make sure the value is spelled correctly.
2. Make sure the role value exists. For example, a common mistake is to specify the invalid role "footer" when the valid role is "contentinfo".
3. Make sure the role is not abstract.
4. Remove any invalid values.

violations.description: Invalid values in ARIA attributes block intended accessibility functions; these functions cannot be actioned if values do not have correct spelling or do not correspond to existing ARIA values that logically apply to a specific attribute.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Set a valid value for each ARIA attribute. Use ONLY valid values for all ARIA attributes.
 
How to fix:
1. Make sure you are using the correct type of value. (For example, some attributes allow only "true" or "false" values, while others allow the value to remain undefined.)
2. Make sure the value is spelled correctly.
3. Consider whether the attribute has a default value that must be modified in order to be valid in the current context.
4. If the attribute references an ID, make sure the ID exists on the page.

violations.recommendation:
Action: Regular text (text below 18 point / 24 pixel, or 14 point / 19 pixel, if bold) must have a color contrast ratio of at least 4.5:1 against its background. Large text (text above 18 point / 24 pixel, or 14 point / 19 pixel, if bold) must have a color contrast ratio of at least 3:1 against its background.
  
How to fix:
For regular text: Make sure its contrast ratio meets or exceeds 4.5:1.
For large text: Make sure its contrast ratio meets or exceeds 3:1.
1. Use higher contrast, compliant colors for text and/or background.
2. Always test and verify your color choices and contrast ratios with a contrast checker, such as the one at https://userway.org/contrast.

violations.description: Text does not meet WCAG 2 AAA enhanced minimum contrast requirements against its background color.

violations.recommendation:
Action: Regular text (text below 18 point / 24 pixel, or 14 point / 19 pixel, if bold) must have a color contrast ratio of at least 7:1 against its background. Large text (text above 18 point / 24 pixel, or 14 point / 19 pixel, if bold) must have a color contrast ratio of at least 4.5:1 against its background.

How to fix:
For regular text: Make sure its contrast ratio meets or exceeds 7:1.
For large text: Make sure its contrast ratio meets or exceeds 4.5:1.
1. Use higher contrast, compliant colors for text and/or background.
2. Always test and verify your color choices and contrast ratios with a contrast checker, such as the one at https://userway.org/contrast.

violations.description: Content must not be locked to a specific device orientation.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Make sure content is not locked to any specific device orientation.

How to fix:
• Make sure no techniques have been used to lock device orientation, including CSS.
• Test content orientation for accessibility to all users in any orientation.

violations.description: All non-interactive elements with mouse or keyboard handlers should have tabindex="0" attribute
violations.errorMessage: Non-interactive element with mouse or keyboard handlers missing tabindex="0" attribute
violations.recommendation: Add a tabindex="0" attribute to the element with the mouse or keyboard handler

violations.description:
This definition list contains inappropriate elements.
A <dl> element (that is, a definition list) must directly contain only properly ordered <dt> and <dd> groups, <script>, or <template> elements.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Make sure each <dl> element is properly structured:
 
How to fix:
Examine and correct all definition lists:
1. Each <dl> element must contain ONLY <dt>, <dd>, <script>, and <template> elements.
2. Each <dl> element must contain one or more <dt> elements.
3. Each <dt> element must contain one or more <dd> elements.

violations.description: These definition list items, e.g., <dt> and <dd> elements, are not contained by a parent <dl> element.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Contain all definition list items in a parent definition list element.
 
How to fix:
Wrap all <dt> and <dd> elements within a parent <dl> element.

violations.description: This page is missing its required <title> element, describing its topic, content, or purpose.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Make sure that all pages have a page title, using the title tag.
  
How to fix:
Include a non-empty <title> element in the <head> section.
 
Your titles should:
1. Accurately describe the page's content and purpose
2. Be unique (no duplicate titles)
3. Keep it simple and concise
4. Use language familiar to the user (no jargon)
5. Include the unique name first, overall site name last

violations.description: All heading elements or elements with role="heading" must have non-empty accessible name
violations.errorMessage: Heading element has an empty accessible name
violations.recommendation: For each heading element and element with role="heading" add an inner text, non-empty "aria-label" attribute, or use "aria-labelledby" attribute that refers to the id of an element with discernible text content

violations.description: All <th> elements or elements with role="rowheader" and role="columnheader" must have discernible text
violations.recommendation: For all <th> elements or elements with role="rowheader" and role="columnheader" add discernible text. If the element is not header, marking it up with a <td>

violations.description: Elements should be attached to correct event listener pairs
violations.errorMessage: Elements are only attached to an event listener that has an incorrect or missing relevant keyboard event listener pair
violations.recommendation: Provide sufficient pairs of event listeners that cover all types of action-triggering sources (key events, click and touch events, focus and blur)

violations.description: <fieldset> element must contain a <legend> element as first child
violations.errorMessage: <fieldset> element lacks a <legend> element as first child
violations.recommendation: Add a descriptive <legend> element as the first child within the <fieldset> element to describe the grouping. For example: <fieldset><legend>Pizza toppings</legend>...</fieldset>

violations.description: Interactive elements in the focus order should have a valid and appropriate role
violations.errorMessage: Interactive element in the focus has an invalid and/or inappropriate role
violations.recommendation: Ensure that the interactive element in the focus have a valid and appropriate role, whether native HTML or a custom ARIA widget

violations.description: The form field has more than one label. This is not allowed.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Remove redundant or multiple labels from all form fields.
 
 How to fix:
 1. Examine form field labels.
 2. Choose the most relevant label; keep it.
 3. Remove all other labels.

violations.description: A <frame> or <iframe> element has both a negative tabindex (e.g., "-1") and focusable content. This is not allowed.
violations.errorMessage: Frame element with focusable content has negative tabindex
violations.recommendation:
Action: Make sure that any focusable content does not also have a negative tabindex attribute.
 
How to fix:
Remove the negative tabindex attribute from all <frame> and <iframe> elements that contain focusable content.

violations.description: A <frame> and <iframe> element does not have an accessible title that describes its contents for screen reader and assistive tech users.
violations.recommendation:
Action:
For each <frame> or <iframe> element, provide an accessible name/title. The name or title should be descriptive, meaningful, and unique.
 
How to fix:
Examine the <frame> or <iframe> element. Does an accessible title exist?
1. If the title does not exist, add it.
2. If the title does exist, but is not accessible, make it accessible.
3. If the title does exist, but is not unique, or not sufficiently descriptive, change it.
 
Use ONE of the following methods:
 
Good
• title attribute
 
Better
• aria-label attribute
 
Best
• aria-labelledby attribute

successCriteria.label: Success Criterion 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (Level A)

1. If the title does not exist, add it.
2. If the title does exist, but is not accessible, make it accessible.
3. If the title does exist, but is not unique, or not sufficiently descriptive, change it.
 
Use ONE of the following methods:
 
Good
• title attribute
 
Better
• aria-label attribute
 
Best
• aria-labelledby attribute

violations.description: This HTML document element is missing a required valid lang attribute or lang code, which is needed for multilingual screen reader announcement with better language-specific vocalization accuracy.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Determine and encode a primary language for the page.
 
How to fix:
1. Identify the page's primary language.
2. Choose the corresponding language code from the IANA Language Subtag Registry
3. Add a lang attribute to the <html> element using the correct language tag for the value that represents the primary language of the page.
4. If a lang attribute is already specified, make sure its value is spelled correctly.

4. If a lang attribute is already specified, make sure its value is spelled correctly.

violations.recommendation:
Action: Change the accessible name to one that matches its purpose. Be sure to set identical links only when they describe the same purpose.

How to fix:
Use the following to describe link purpose:
• aria-label
• link text
• alt attribute

successCriteria.label: Success Criterion 2.4.4 Link Purpose (In Context) (Level A)

violations.description: This image is missing required alt text. Without alt text, there is no way to equally convey the image meaning and intent to screen reader and assistive tech users.
violations.recommendation: Action: Add meaningful alt text if the image conveys useful information. Add a blank (null) alt text if the image should be ignored. How to fix: 1. Determine whether the image is meaningful or decorative: a. IF an image conveys useful information that is NOT available through other page content, THEN it is meaningful. b. IF an image could be removed from the page with no impact on meaning or function, THEN it is decorative. 2. Add an alt attribute: a. If the element is decorative, add an empty (null) alt attribute ( alt="" ). b. If the element is meaningful, provide descriptive alternative text using one of the following methods: Good • title attribute Better • aria-label • aria-labelledby attribute Best • alt attribute

violations.description: "alt" attribute value of element must not contain more than 256 characters
violations.errorMessage: The "alt" attribute exceeds the recommended length
violations.recommendation: Shorten the length of the "alt" attribute to be 5â€“10 words. If a longer description is necessary, wrap the element within a

violations.description: The "alt" attribute of element must not contain extraneous text
violations.recommendation: Delete from the "alt" attribute extraneous text such as "image of", "photo of", "graphic of" , "illustration of", "icon of", etc. For example, replace: alt="A photo of an astronaut performing a space walk" with alt="An astronaut performing a space walk"

violations.description: All elements that are wrapped in must have "alt" text
violations.recommendation: Delete from the "alt" attribute extraneous text such as "image of", "photo of", "graphic of" , "illustration of", "icon of", etc. For example, replace: alt="A photo of an astronaut performing a space walk" with alt="An astronaut performing a space walk"

violations.description: Text of buttons and links should not be repeated in the image alternative text
violations.errorMessage: Ensure image alternative is not repeated as text
violations.recommendation: Left an "alt" attribute of image empty or modify it so it does not repeat the parent elements text

violations.description: Each element with unique value of "src" attribute must have unique value of "alt" attribute
violations.errorMessage: Two or more images with unique value of "src" attribute have the same "alt" attribute
violations.recommendation: Write each image's "alt" attribute to uniquely describe that image's meaning or purpose

successCriteria.label: Success Criterion 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (Level A)

violations.description: This input button does not have an accessible name with discernible text. That is an accessibility failure.
violations.errorMessage: Missing: accessible name on input button
violations.recommendation:
Action: Add an accessible name for each input button.
 
How to fix:
Use one of the following methods:
 
Good
• title attribute
 
Better
• Non-empty value attribute
• No value attribute (applies only if type is submit or reset; causes the type value to be reported as the accessible name)
• aria-label attribute
 
Best
• aria-labelledby attribute

successCriteria.label: Success Criterion 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (Level A)

violations.description: This input button does not have an accessible name with discernible text. That is an accessibility failure.
violations.errorMessage: Missing: alt text on image button
violations.recommendation:
Action: Add alternative text that describes the input button's purpose.
 
How to fix:
Use one of the following methods:
 
Good
• title attribute
 
Better
• aria-label attribute
• aria-labelledby attribute
 
Best
• alt attribute

violations.description: All "id" attributes must have a valid value
violations.recommendation: Either populate the "id" attribute with a unique value or remove the "id" attribute entirely

violations.description: Screen readers and other assistive technology cannot understand the context of a <i> element as italic text can play numerous roles
violations.recommendation: If the text should be emphasized semantically, use the <em> element instead. If the text should be marked in another language, add 'lang' attribute with a valid value. If the text is highlighted as a visual effect, CSS should be used to do this

violations.recommendation:
Action: Be sure to distinguish links by methods other than color alone.
  
How to fix:
1. Add an additional visual cue on hover, such as an underline, or a change in font style.
2. Or, increase font size for links.
 
3. Do NOT use color alone to identify links; see above. However, if color is ONE of the methods distinguishing links, make sure to use a color that contrasts sufficiently both with its background, and with its surrounding text, so that it can be easily discerned by users who are partly or wholly color-blind.

violations.description:
This list does not have correct list markup / hierarchy.
Parent list elements, e.g., <ul>, <ol>, or <menu>, may ONLY directly contain the following child elements: <li>, <script>, or <template>.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Correct all list markup errors.
 
How to fix:
For each list element (<ol>, <ul> or <menu>), ordered or unordered:
 
1. Make sure all list content is contained within <li> elements.
2. Do not use a role attribute to override the native semantics of a <li> element.
3. If you include any other HTML elements, enclose them within <li> elements.

violations.description:
This list does not have correct list markup / hierarchy.
 All <li> list items must be contained by the following parent list elements: <ul>, <ol>, or <menu>
violations.recommendation:
Action: Set all <li> elements inside a containing <ul>, <ol>, or <menu> parent element.
 
How to fix:
For each <li> list item:
 
1. Enclose the <li> element in a <ul> or <ol> element (or in a parent element with role="list" ).
2. Do not use a role attribute to override the native semantics of the <ul> or <ol> element.

violations.description: The deprecated <marquee> element is in use.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Remove <marquee> elements.
 
How to fix:
1. Remove any existing <marquee> code, or any similar code structure.
2. Be sure to avoid coding text in any way that would cause it to move across the screen.

violations.description: The <meta http-equiv="refresh"> element is in use for delayed refresh.
violations.errorMessage: Illicit refresh attribute in meta element
violations.recommendation:
Action: Remove http-equiv="refresh" from all <meta> elements.
 
How to fix:
If a page refresh is required:
 
1. Implement the refresh using a script.
2. AND, offer a mechanism for users to turn off, extend, or adjust the timing of the page refresh.

violations.description: The <meta http-equiv="refresh"> element is in use for delayed refresh. This is not allowed.
violations.errorMessage: Illicit refresh attribute in meta element
violations.recommendation:
Action: Remove the refresh attribute from the meta element.

How to fix:
1. Remove http-equiv="refresh" from all meta elements.
2. IF a page refresh is required, then:
  2a. It should be set up via JavaScript.
  2b. Users must be given added options to:
         • Pause refresh
         • Extend refresh intervals
         • Turn off refresh option

violations.description: These audio or video elements are set to play automatically, without user trigger. Audio elements must not autoplay for more than 3 seconds without an available mechanism to stop or mute the sound. This applies to both <audio> and <video> elements.
violations.display: No autoplay audio more than 3 seconds without controls
violations.recommendation:
Action: Make sure audio or video does not autoplay for more than 3 seconds without offering users an opportunity to stop or mute the sound.
 
How to fix:
Use one of the following solutions:
1. Whenever possible, play audio or video only on user request.
2. Stop autoplaying audio automatically after 3 seconds.
3. Add an accessible control mechanism to <audio> and <video> elements, so that users can stop or mute the sound. This control should not affect the overall system volume.

violations.description: <video> or <audio> element should not autoplay audio for more than 3 seconds
violations.display: No autoplay audio for more than 3 seconds
violations.errorMessage: <video> or <audio> element plays audio automatically for more than 3 seconds
violations.recommendation: Make auto playing the audio shorter than 3 seconds

violations.recommendation:
Action: Add alternative text for each <object> element.
 
How to fix:
Use one of the following methods:
 
Good
• title attribute, or inner text
 
Better
• aria-label attribute
 
Best
• aria-labelledby attribute

violations.description: An element with role="img" is missing a required alternative text.
violations.display: Alternate text for element with role="image"
violations.recommendation:
Action: Add alternative text for each element with role="img":
 
How to fix:
1. Determine whether the image as a whole is meaningful or decorative:
  1a. An image is meaningful if it conveys information that is not available through other page content.
  1b. An image is decorative if it could be removed from the page with no impact on meaning or function.
2. If the image is meaningful:
  2a. Add concise alt text that conveys the image meaning using one of the following attributes:
  • aria-label
  • aria-labelledby
  • title
  2b. Observe the image. Does it include visible text? If yes, be sure to include any visible text in the alt text.
3. If the image is decorative, replace role="img" with role="presentation" or role="none"

violations.recommendation:
Action: Make sure scrollable content in an element is accessible via keyboard.
 
How to fix:
For each element with the overflow property set to auto or scroll, make sure the element itself is focusable or contains a focusable element.
 
Some scrollable elements (such as <input type="text"> are natively focusable.
Elements that are not natively focusable (such as <div> elements) can be made focusable by adding the attribute tabindex="0".

violations.description: A <select> elements is missing a required programatically associated accessible name.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Add an accessible name for each <select> element.
 
How to fix:
Use one of the following methods:
 
Good
 • title attribute
 
Better
 • aria-label attribute
 • aria-labelledby attribute referencing visible text
 
Best
 • Explicit <label> element
 • Implicit (wrapped) <label> element

violations.recommendation:
Action: Make touch target larger, with a comfortable space margin around it.

How to fix:
 1. Make touch target at least 44x44 CSS pixels, or larger.
 2. If the touch target is smaller than 44x44, be sure to leave a 44px space between this touch target and any other touch target.

violations.description: In this large table, a cell containing information has no table header.
violations.recommendation: In this large table, a cell containing information has no table header. This is not allowed.

violations.description: This table uses the headers attribute. However, this table contains a cell that refers to a cell located in another table. This is not allowed.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Make sure that in a table with the headers attribute, no cells refer to a cell outside the same table.
 
How to fix:
If the headers attribute is set for your table, use one of the following techniques:
1. Add the <scope> attribute value <col> or <row> to each <th> set within a <tr> element.
2. Or, for headers that span columns/rows, add spanning header markup: <colgroup> or <rowgroup> values in the <scope> attribute.

The <scope> values will examine all references in the table that point to header columns and rows, and make sure that the references connect to particular <td> elements.

violations.description: In this table, a table header with a column or row header role is not associated with a table data element. This is not allowed.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Make sure each <th> element, and each element with the columnheader or rowheader roles, has an associated data cell.
 
How to fix:
For each <th> element:
1. Make sure it does not use the <headers> attribute.
2. Make sure it is only used in a table with a single header row or single header column.
3. Make sure the <th> element uses the <scope> attribute.
4. If no cell is associated with the header, correctly associate the <th> element with its corresponding <td> element.

violations.description: One or more tr elements, without an ARIA-assigned role, not intentionally hidden in the DOM and available to assistive technologies, contains two or more descendant elements (without an ARIA-assigned role) that have been given a scope attribute set to the text value 'row'.
violations.display: One or more tr elements, contains two or more descendant elements that have a scope attribute set to the text value 'row'.
violations.errorMessage: This {{tag-name}} should not contain two or more descendant elements (without an ARIA-assigned role) that have been given a scope attribute set to the text value: row
violations.recommendation: This <tr> should not contain two or more descendant elements (without an ARIA-assigned role) that have been given a scope attribute set to the text value: row

violations.errorMessage: The alt attribute is not allowed on this element

violations.description: The lang attribute has an invalid language value.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Add a valid lang attribute value.
 
How to fix:
1. Identify the language for the text.
2. Choose the corresponding language code from the IANA Language Subtag Registry.
3. Make sure the value is spelled correctly.

violations.description: This HTML5 <video> element is missing a required captions track.
violations.recommendation:
Action: Add a captions track to the video element.
 
How to fix:
Add a captions track as a track element with kind="captions".
 
Captions should be synchronized with the video, and should convey dialogue, musical cues, sound cues, sound effects, and any other meaningful, relevant audio information.
